return_on_assets=pd.read_csv("sp_500_return_on_assets_actual.csv")
del return_on_assets['Unnamed: 0']
cols = ['2021', '2020','2019', '2018', '2017','2016']
return_on_assets.loc[:,cols] = return_on_assets.loc[:,cols].fillna(method='ffill', axis = 1)

In [16]:
pdList=[esg_scores,return_on_assets,return_on_equity,return_on_investment_capital,ebitda]
prof_var_ls=['ESG Score','ROA','ROE','ROIC','EBITDA']

del return_on_assets['Symbol']
del return_on_equity['Symbol']
del return_on_investment_capital['Symbol']
del ebitda['Symbol']
prof_variables_df=pd.concat(pdList, axis=1)
for i in prof_var_ls:
    prof_variables_df=prof_variables_df[prof_variables_df[i] != 0]

industries=['Communication Services', 'Consumer Discretionary', 'Consumer Staples',
       'Energy', 'Financials', 'Health Care', 'Industrials',
       'Information Technology', 'Materials', 'Real Estate', 'Utilities']

          health_care_df,industrials_df,information_technology_df,materials_df,real_estate_df,utilities_df]

Correlation Analysis¶

In the above table, negative numbers shows increase in Environment, Social and Governance scores decreases the scores of other variables, whereas positive correlation shows increase in ESG scores increase the other ratios.

ROA:¶

Overall, there is increase in return on assets (ROA) ratios for sectors, 'Communication Services', 'Consumer Staples', 'Financials', 'Health Care', 'Information Technology', 'Real Estate' with increase in ESG scores whereas for sectors 'Consumer Discretionary', 'Energy', 'Industrials', 'Materials', 'Utilities' the ROA decreases with increase in ESG scores.

ROE:¶

Overall, there is increase in return on equity (ROE) ratios for sectors, 'Communication Services', 'Consumer Staples', 'Financials', 'Health Care', 'Industrials', 'Real Estate', 'Utilities' with increase in ESG scores whereas for sectors 'Information Technology', 'Materials', 'Consumer Discretionary', 'Energy', the ROE decreases with increase in ESG scores.

ROIC:¶

Overall, there is increase in return on invested capitals (ROIC) ratios for sectors 'Communication Services', 'Consumer Discretionary', 'Consumer Staples', 'Financials', 'Information Technology', with increase in ESG scores whereas for sectors, 'Energy', 'Health Care', 'Industrials', 'Materials' , 'Real Estate' , 'Utilities', the ROIC decreases with increase in ESG scores.

EBITDA:¶

Overall, there is increase in return on Earnings before interest tax depreciation and amortisation (EBITDA) margin ratios for all sectors with increase in ESG score.

prof_vars = ['ROA', 'ROE','ROIC', 'EBITDA']
Industries=['Communication Services', 'Consumer Discretionary', 'Consumer Staples',
       'Energy', 'Financials', 'Health Care', 'Industrials',
       'Information Technology', 'Materials', 'Real Estate', 'Utilities']
for i in range(4):
    cc_ls = new_p[prof_vars[i]].to_list()
    print(prof_vars[i])
    print("=================================")
    for j in range(11):
        cc = cc_ls[j]
        #print(cc)
        cc = round(cc, 2)
        if (cc >= 0.8 and cc <= 1):
            print(Industries[j], ": Very Strong Positive (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= 0.6 and cc <= 0.79):
            print(Industries[j], ": Strong Positive (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= 0.4 and cc <= 0.59):
            print(Industries[j], ": Moderate Positive (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= 0.2 and cc <= 0.39):
            print(Industries[j], ": Weak Positive (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= 0 and cc < 0.19):
            print(Industries[j], ": Very Weak Positive (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= -1 and cc <= -0.8):
            print(Industries[j], ": Very Strong Negative (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= -0.79 and cc <= -0.6):
            print(Industries[j], ": Strong Negative (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= -0.59 and cc <= -0.4):
            print(Industries[j], ": Moderate Negative (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= -0.39 and cc <= -0.2):
            print(Industries[j], ": Weak Negative (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= -0.19 and cc <= -0.01):
            print(Industries[j], ": Very Weak Negative (", cc,")")
            
    print()

Correlation Analysis¶

In the above table, negative numbers shows increase in Environment, Social and Governance scores decreases the scores of other variables, whereas positive correlation shows increase in ESG scores increase the other ratios.

Diluted earnings per share (EPS):¶

There is an increase in EPS ratios for sectors 'Communication Services', 'Consumer Discretionary', 'Financials', 'Health Care', 'Industrials', 'Information Technology', 'Utilities' with increase in ESG scores, whereas there is a decrease in EPS ratios for sectors 'Consumer Staples', 'Energy', 'Materials','Real Estate' with decrease in ESG scores.

Dividend per share (DPS):¶

It showed positive correlation of ESG scores for all of the sectors. All the sectors DPS increased with increase in ESG scores, except sector 'Real Estate' which showed negative correlation.

Dividend yield (DY) :¶

There is positive trend between ESG scores and all the sectors for Dividend Yield, except 'Utilities'.

Price to earnings ratio (PER):¶

Overall, there is decrease in Price to Earnings ratios (PER) for all sectors as ESG score increases.

Enterprise value (EV):¶

Overall, there is increase in Enterprise Value ratios for all sectors with increase in ESG score.

Price to sales per share ratio (PTS):¶

Overall, there is decrease in Price to sales per share ratio for sectors 'Communication Services', 'Consumer Staples', 'Energy','Industrials', 'Information Technology', 'Real Estate' as ESG score increases. However, there is increase in PTS ratio for the rest of the sectors.

Price to book value (P/BV):¶

Overall, there is decrease in Price to Book ratios for sectors 'Consumer Staples','Energy', 'Industrials','Information Technology', 'Materials' with increase in ESG scores whereas the rest of the sectors shows increasing trend with increase in ESG scores.

Identifying how weakly or strongly correlated the variables are¶

ev_vars = ['EPS', 'DPS','DY', 'PER', 'EV', 'PTS', 'PBV']
Industries=['Communication Services', 'Consumer Discretionary', 'Consumer Staples',
       'Energy', 'Financials', 'Health Care', 'Industrials',
       'Information Technology', 'Materials', 'Real Estate', 'Utilities']
for i in range(7):
    cc_ls = new_ev[ev_vars[i]].to_list()
    print(ev_vars[i])
    print("=================================")
    for j in range(11):
        cc = cc_ls[j]
        cc = round(cc,2)
        #print(cc)
        if (cc >= 0.8 and cc <= 1):
            print(Industries[j], ": Very Strong Positive (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= 0.6 and cc <= 0.79):
            print(Industries[j], ": Strong Positive (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= 0.4 and cc <= 0.59):
            print(Industries[j], ": Moderate Positive (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= 0.2 and cc <= 0.39):
            print(Industries[j], ": Weak Positive (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= 0 and cc < 0.19):
            print(Industries[j], ": Very Weak Positive (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= -1 and cc <= -0.8):
            print(Industries[j], ": Very Strong Negative (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= -0.79 and cc <= -0.6):
            print(Industries[j], ": Strong Negative (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= -0.59 and cc <= -0.4):
            print(Industries[j], ": Moderate Negative (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= -0.39 and cc <= -0.2):
            print(Industries[j], ": Weak Negative (", cc,")")
        elif (cc >= -0.19 and cc <= -0.01):
            print(Industries[j], ": Very Weak Negative (", cc,")")
            
    print()
